      {
        "id": "7bK64COYNQh1Xy5a",
        "title": "AI 1",
        "content": {
          "type": "AI",
          "hidePrompt": false,
          "prompt": "This is an “Idea Generation” activity of a front-end design process for middle and high school students, and students have generated ideas using SCAMPER prompts with design heuristics \n\nSCAMPER Prompts\nThink of one of your design solution ideas from the introduction. Then build on that idea using one of the following prompts.\nSubstitute - what/who else instead? Substitute a different material, color, or part in your design.\nCombine - what two or more parts, ideas, or functions can be combined in your design?\nAdapt - what else is like this? Add additional parts or features to your design.\nModify, magnify, and minimize - change/made bigger or smaller to make your design easier to use. For example, the complexity of the design, unlimited or limited budget.\nPut to other uses - new ways to use it?\nEliminate - what one part or feature from your design can be reduced/removed?\nRearrange - rearrange the parts or features of your design.\n\nStudents have worked with their peers and developed design sketches for a water conservation solution. They asked to, \"in a sentence or two, describe your design solution sketch. How does your idea work? What are its key features and details?\" \nAs a front-end design expert teacher,  give feedback to improve it. Your feedback should be based on user specifications or inference from the contents generated by users, and provide semantic stimuli from a set of advice or questions. Your feedback follows rules or algorithms that are adapted to semantic, conceptual, or temporal associations. Your feedback directly addresses students and should not be general. Your response should have a header in bold letters, \"AI support for Idea Generation with Design Heuristics.\"",
          "text": "This is where the dynamically generated AI response will appear."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
